Already 6 feet tall, Brian Sanchez decided to gain 7 more inches through double limb-lengthening surgery‚Äînot for height itself, but because he felt his proportions were off. The 33-year-old mortgage broker from Georgia compared his natural build to the "Thumb Thumbs" from Spy Kids, believing his legs were too short for his torso.

Two separate procedures in Turkey at the Live Life Taller clinic‚Äîone breaking and extending his tibia and fibula in December 2022, another lengthening his femurs in March 2023‚Äîbrought him to nearly 6'7". Total investment: $106,000.

His wife Nidia, standing at 5'10", now has a drastically different view when they're together. While critics questioned why someone already above average height would pursue such extreme measures, Sanchez expressed complete satisfaction with his decision and new perspective.

The story, discussed on The Joe Rogan Experience with Derek from More Plates More Dates, raises questions about where personal body autonomy meets unconventional choices. @thejrecompanion breaks down the full conversation in the episode links.

The supplement world is full of hype, but creatine continues to prove itself through rigorous scientific scrutiny. @foundmyfitness breaks down why this compound deserves attention beyond the gym‚Äîfrom powering cellular energy through ATP production to emerging data suggesting cognitive enhancement during periods of mental strain and exhaustion.

One persistent concern? The hair loss myth. Dr. Layne Norton (@biolayne) addresses this head-on in his recent podcast appearance, clarifying that while one small study showed elevated DHT levels, no actual link to hair loss has been established in the research.

Daily dosing recommendations hover between 5-10 grams, and the old-school loading protocol is now considered unnecessary by most experts. Experiencing digestive issues? Split your dose into smaller servings throughout the day.

For the complete deep-dive into Layne's supplement recommendations, episode 94 of the FoundMyFitness podcast delivers three and a half hours of evidence-based insights. Stream it on Apple Podcasts, Spotify, or YouTube, with detailed show notes at foundmyfitness.com/episodes/layne-norton
